    one:"Exp 238 found that faster creatures earn more food in continuous space, but we could not tell if it was NAVIGATION skill or just covering more ground. This experiment cost-neutralises coverage — the cost structure makes pure distance-arithmetic net-negative at every speed — so only genuine navigation to the food bumps can pay. It works: the food-navigating creatures profit (mean +0.444 per step above the random-billiard baseline) while the flat field and the blind billiard both lose money. The faster mutant (speed 1.1) also invades from rarity (8/8) under these conditions. Honest catch: there was no stable crowd size during the test — the population was still growing — so the invasion measures 'does the mutant grow faster from a small founding group,' not 'can it spread in a crowded equilibrium population.' That is r-selection (growth-phase competition), not the classical equilibrium test. Exp 240 re-runs it at a verified stable population size to find out if the signal survives.",
