    one:"Exp 239 found invasion in continuous space, but there was no stable population size — so it was a growth-phase artifact, not a genuine equilibrium invasion. This experiment adds a density-dependent brake (food regrows slower as the population fills up) so the resident (speed-1.0) reaches a VERIFIED stable size of ~374 creatures across all three random seeds over 3000 steps. At that stable crowd level, a small group of faster mutants (speed-1.1, starting at ~5% of the population) increases in frequency in all 8 tests — it drives a population explosion because at crowd density 374 it eats ~43% more food per step than the residents. So the core prediction of the local-gradient wall — a costed trait saturates at equilibrium and cannot invade from rarity — FAILS here. The honest catches: the faster type has no stable population size of its own (once it becomes common it triggers a food-web collapse), so the invasion drives runaway, not evolution to a new stable optimum. And this is one set of parameters. Candidate: the first time in the project a costed trait invades from rarity at verified equilibrium, but runaway + one-regime means it needs more evidence before becoming a confirmed breakthrough.",
